full_text: In this demonstration, I will show how to assign an object using automated assignment, and how to assign an object explicitly to a specific user. Darlene Olson, an adjuster in a workers' compensation group at Succeed Insurance, receives a call from Jennifer Albee. Note that there are no activities in Darlene's activities list. She's reporting an injury accident on behalf of Georgetown Roofing. The accident took place today at about 8.30 a.m. Ms. Albee is a manager in Georgetown's Human Resources Department. The injured worker is named Joe Thornsby. Ms. Albee has also provided Mr. Thornsby's Social Security Number. Mr. Thornsby was clearing out the roof gutters at Georgetown's premises when he fell off a ladder. He had begun work at 6 this morning. Mr. Thornsby appears to have a broken tibia. Darlene quickly enters what is known about the injury at this time. Mr. Thornsby's leg required medical attention. An EMT crew evaluated him, splinted his leg, and took him to hospital for x-rays. It is expected that he will miss some work time, though the actual time is not yet known. In the lost time tab, Darlene enters details. Mr. Thornsby earns $16.25 per hour, 8 hours a day, 5 days a week, equal to $660 per week. That is all the information Ms. Albee provides to Darlene at this time, so she will go ahead and complete the entry of the claim. Darlene uses automated assignment to assign the claim. She could also use search to assign the claim to a specific person. The claim has been assigned to a group, Comp, Team B, and to a user, Candice Payne. Darlene can now view the claim. Although the claim has been assigned to another adjuster, Darlene is going to go ahead and make the initial contact with the medical provider. Looking at the work plan for the claim, she finds the activity to contact the provider and clicks its checkbox. Darlene is going to assign the activity to herself. Rather than using automated assignment, which would assign the activity back to Candice Payne, she selects her own name from the list of eligible users and clicks Assign. When Darlene returns to the activities list on her desktop, we see that Darlene has one activity, though it is not due today. But if she looks at a week, the activity now appears. This concludes the assigning entities in the user interface demonstration.
